'''Emily Fleur Shuckburgh''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} is a climate scientist and science communicator. She leads the Data Science Group and is Deputy head of the Polar Oceans Team at the [[British Antarctic Survey]] and is also a fellow of [[Darwin College, Cambridge|Darwin College Cambridge]]. Her research interests include the dynamics of the atmosphere, oceans and climate. She is a theoretician, [[numerical modeller]] and observational scientist.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bas.ac.uk/profile/emsh/|title=Emily Shuckburgh - British Antarctic Survey|website=http://www.bas.ac.uk |language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" ! colspan="2" |Emily Shuckburgh |- !Nationality |British |- !Alma mater |Magdalen College (BA), University of Oxford; Cambridge University (PhD) |- | colspan="2" |'''Scientific career''' |- !Fields |Climate Science, meteorology, oceanography |- !Institutions |British Antarctic Survey, MIT, Ecole Normale Superieure, Paris, University of Cambridge |}
== Career == Following a BS in Mathematics at the [[University of Oxford]], Emily Shuckburgh completed a PhD at the [[University of Cambridge]] in Applied mathematics. After post doctoral research at [[École normale supérieure (Paris)|Ecole Normal Superieure]] in Paris and at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], she joined the [[British Antarctic Survey]] where she leads the [[Natural Environment Research Council]] Ocean Regulation of Climate by Heat and Carbon Sequestration and Transports (ORCHESTRA) project<ref name=":0" />. As a fellow of [[Darwin College, Cambridge]] she holds several positions within the [[University of Cambridge]]; she is an associate fellow of the [[Centre for Science and Policy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.csap.cam.ac.uk/network/emily-shuckburgh/|title=Dr Emily Shuckburgh - Networks of evidence and expertise for public policy|website=http://www.csap.cam.ac.uk |language=en|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref> and fellow of the [[Cambridge Institute for Sustainability Leadership]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cisl.cam.ac.uk/directory/emily-shuckburgh|title=Dr Emily Shuckburgh, Fellow — Cambridge Institute for Sustainability Leadership|last=kla29@cam.ac.uk|website=http://www.cisl.cam.ac.uk |language=en|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>. Her research interests include the dynamics of the atmosphere, oceans and climate. She is a theoretician, [[numerical modeller]] and observational scientist.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bas.ac.uk/profile/emsh/|title=Emily Shuckburgh - British Antarctic Survey|website=http://www.bas.ac.uk |language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>
Dr Shuckburgh is a fellow of the [[Royal Meteorological Society]], where she is co-Chair of their Climate Science Communications Group and a former Chair of their Scientific Publications Committee<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rmets.org/about-us/people/frmets-register?pageNum_frmets=3&totalRows_frmets=438&page=11|title=FRMetS Register {{!}} Royal Meteorological Society|website=http://www.rmets.org |language=en|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>. She has also acted as an advisor to the [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK Government]] on behalf of the [[Natural Environment Research Council]] <ref name=":0" />.
=== Science Communication === Dr Shuckburgh has written on [[Climate Science|climate science]], [[sustainability]] and [[women in science]] for publications including the [[Financial Times]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/49c88c92-0115-11e4-a938-00144feab7de|title=An opportunity for innovation rather than a challenge|date=2014-08-01|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>, [[The New Statesman]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://legacy.bas.ac.uk/staff-profiles/webspace/emsh/innovativebritainsupp.pdf|title=Innovative Britain|last=|first=|date=|work=The New Statesman|access-date=}}</ref> and the [[Sunday Times]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://legacy.bas.ac.uk/staff-profiles/webspace/emsh/sundaytimes.pdf|title=Women's Lab|last=|first=|date=|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=}}</ref>. She serves on the board of the [[Campaign for Science and Engineering]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencecampaign.org.uk/about-us/case-team.html|title=CaSE {{!}} CaSE Team|last=CaSE|website=http://www.sciencecampaign.org.uk |access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>.
In 2016 she was awarded an OBE for services to science and the public communication of science<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.darwin.cam.ac.uk/news/new-years-honours-dr-emily-shuckburgh-obe|title=New Year's Honours - Dr Emily Shuckburgh OBE {{!}} http://www.darwin.cam.ac.uk |website=http://www.darwin.cam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>. She co-authored Climate Change (A Ladybird Expert Book) with [[Charles, Prince of Wales|HRH The Prince of Wales]] and [[Tony Juniper]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/973272219|title=Climate change|last=1948-|first=Charles, Prince of Wales,|others=Juniper, Tony,, Shuckburgh, Emily,, Palmer, Ruth, 1954-|isbn=9780718185855|location=London|oclc=973272219}}</ref>
