'''Explorer 26''' was an [[United States|American]] [[satellite]] launched on December 21, 1964, as part of [[NASA]]'s [[Explorers program]]. Its primary mission was to study the Earth's magnetic field.<ref name=NSSDCA>{{cite web|url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraftDisplay.do?id=1964-086A|title=Explorer 26|publisher=NASA Space Science Data Coordinated Archive|accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref>

==Design==
Explorer 26 was a spin-stabilized satellite weighing 45.8 kg. It carried 5 experiments: Solid-State Electron Detector, Omnidirectional and Unidirectional Electron and Proton Fluxes, Fluxgate Magnetometers, Proton-Electron Scintillation Detector, and Solar Cell Damage. <ref name=NSSDCA></ref> The Solar Cell Damage experiment was intended to quantify the degradation of solar cell performance due to radiation, and evaluate the effectiveness of glass shields at preventing this degradation. <ref>{{citation | publisher=Goddard Space Flight Center | title=Preliminary Results of the Explorer XXVI Solar Cell Experiment | year=1965 | format=PDF | author1=Luther W. Slifer | author2=Stephen G McCarron | url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19660007969.pdf}}</ref>

